CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with episodes of bilateral hand shaking and
loss of awareness. These episodes stopped after the patient began Depakote therapy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were preformed. This was a 1 hour sleep-deprived study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing and anterior
spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background
slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this
EEG nor in the previous EEG. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old male with recurrent vertigo and fatigue.
MEDICATIONS: Os-Cal, Nexium, Lexapro, Albuterol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with 9.5 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles are observed
in stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation is performed after the patient has been asleep.
There is a driving response observed, though the patient is drifting in an out of sleep.
Hyperventilation produces a scant amount of background slowing.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed in this EEG. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important
consideration, a repeat study capturing one of his spells is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old left handed male with migraine headaches and visual scintillations.  Head trauma.

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, background EEG includes a well organized 10 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness produces an increase in background theta. POSTS are observed in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. The patient drifts back into stage I sleep.

HR: 	60 bpm

IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately  organized with 10.5 Hz, 30 microvolt alpha rhythm and a small amount of wicket activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in the record. A  normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of seizure or stroke and correlation with imaging and history may be appropriate.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low voltage, but there is
an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of background beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing in the background. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by an increase in theta. Hypersynchronous activity is noted in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 	90 bpm

IMPRESSION:   EEG at the limits of normal.

CLINICAL CORR  ELATION: There are no epileptiform features observed. If further characterization of her epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed male with head trauma in 1982, now losing track of time, depression,  anxiety, forgetfulness. Episodes of forgetfulness increasing in stress but none for the last month.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Glyburide, Actoplus, Aceon
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Occasional temporal wicket is observed. The patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background followed by drowsiness.  More extensive stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are observed later on in the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The wicket activity described above is a normal variant.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39 year old right handed male with daily headaches, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine,  Zolpidem, Elavil, Cymbalta, Norvasc, Gabapentin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and primarily asleep EEG with photic stimulation but without hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and posts.   The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and has limited wakefulness.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The primarily sleep EEG could be due to sleep deprivation or other disturbances like hypersomnolence, or even a sleep-deprived EEG. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   48 year old male with a history of tremor during sleep which began in July 2009.  The patient has a history of an MVA in June 2009 and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Valtrex, Nexium, Singulair, Metoprolol, Verapamil, Furosemide, Doxazosin, Flax seed oil, Omega fish oil.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low-voltage but well­ defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Features of drowsiness include an increase of beta.  Hyperventilation produces background slowing.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, and a low-voltage pattern is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with a feeling of disequilibrium
and presyncope, admitted in July 2009.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10
Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in background slowing. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes,
spindles and POSTS. The patient is quite sleepy and transitions in and out of stage II
sleep. The POSTS are of slightly higher amplitude on the left. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The
amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old female presented with syncope and toe ulceration.
MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the
record. There is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified. Features of drowsiness
including increase in beta followed by vertexes, K complexes, and spindles. With
arousal, the patient does achieve an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed in the
record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old woman with multiple events in the clinic today admitted with episode of unresponsiveness  and mutism.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  The patient is awake and cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well defined 9.3 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage fronto-central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of rhythmic theta.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this record was
recorded immediately after this patient's multiple and prolonged events. Hence, not only were the behaviors unusual for seizures, but there was no postictal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   59 year old right handed female with headaches and sharp occipital pain.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is awake for most of the study, however, is in and out of drowsiness.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG shows a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with 25 mV.  In addition, when drowsy the patient has 5 Hz temporal waves and some vertex waves.  Also noted is a rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness (RMTD) which is a normal variant, entered during photic stimulation.  The patient is seen to have driving at 7 Hz.



HR  :


84 bpm with occasional PVCs when drowsy.



IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy  Clinical evaluation of PVCs in sleep may be valuable.

MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, Metoprolol, Renagel, ASA, PhosLo


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic simulation was completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. Lambda waves are observed in the background. There is a generous amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity and muscle artifact as the patient is not particularly cooperative. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing, occasional vertex waves are observed. Photic stimulation elicits a subtle
driving response.


HR:	96 bpm


IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Lambda waves are a normal phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old right handed male with a history of epilepsy with the onset at the age of 5.  The patient has been seizure-free for approximately 5 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The study is performed with photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient begins the study in wakefulness and displays a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with 50 mV. There is higher amplitude on the left than
the right. Throughout the study, the patient transitions in and out of sleep.  During sleep a few vertex waves are noted.  There are posts and sleep spindles.  During photic stimulation there is no reactivity.  During hyperventilation an increased theta with mild slowing is noted.
HR:	N/A
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity is noted. A normal EEG do not exclude diagnosis of epilepsy.

record. The background features are acceptable for a patient of this advanced age.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 14
characterized by tonic-clonic seizures in sleep but with an episode of staring in August
2009.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. HR:	72 bpm

CLINICAL HISTORY:  28 year old woman with episodes of leg shaking and unresponsiveness.  Bipolar disease and depression.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient appears to be tense.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD:  The background EEG includes an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with muscle artifact and beta.   Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR:   60 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The beta and the muscle artifact can be observed in an individual receiving benzodiazepines or in an anxious person.  No epileptiform features were seen.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old right handed woman with syncope, intermittent dizziness, lightheadedness, loss of consciousness 5-7 times per week.
MEDICATIONS: Naprosyn and Elavil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video-EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-developed 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in amplitude.  Beta activity is noted in stage I sleep.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:	55 bpm and slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. The bradycardia may be evaluated clinically.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a loss of consciousness this past Monday, hypersomnolence today prior to thyroidectomy. Ongoing confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Ventolin, Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage II  sleep with vertex, K complexes and spindles.  Little testing is performed to assess for cognitive testing.  The patient is stimulated and when she is awake, the background includes a well-defined, 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates an excessively sleepy individual but normal awake through stage II sleep.  Morphology or wave forms are noted. Additional evaluation for the cause for her excessive drowsiness might be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	41   year old right handed male with recurrent panic attacks and syncopal episodes.

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.   This is an awake and sleep record.

HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed. The sleepiness and the generalized beta may be due to the patient's medications.

HR: 72 bpm and irregular

history of recurrent subdural hematomas, there are no epileptiform features noted.

Hypnagogic hypersynchrony, however, is a normal finding.

deprivation might account for some of the features described above.

At 11:59, the patient is awake. He shifts about. He is awake during photic stimulation which
elicits a brief driving response.
The patient has a spell during the EEG. This is at 12:10. at 12:10:56, he is moving about. He is
unresponsive with a technician. During the section at 12:10:52, the patient has right facial
twitching and he has some movements of his left arm. He does not answer questions to the
technologist. The patient is not entirely on camera. The EEG demonstrates an awake pattern
with an artifact at C3T3. He is amnestic for the event. Unfortunately during this spell the
technician is trying to repair the C3 electrode. He is described as having alternating right facial
or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits but with unusual behavior.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the electrode problems, there was no EEG scalp
signature for this patient's behavior.

Afterward she feels drained and tired but the EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second EEG for this individual. During both EEGs, the patient had behaviors characteristic of nonepileptic seizures with characteristic behavior, crying in the absence of epileptiform activity.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.   This is an awake though stage II sleep record.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  Prominent breech rhythm is noted. There is an asymmetry noted with focal slowing in the left temporal region and disruption of faster frequency activity.  Wicket activity is noted. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, POSTS, and spindles. Hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep.  It does not significantly activate the record.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified, although wicket activity and a breech rhythm were noted.  If further characterization for epileptiform activity is needed, EEG monitoring may be required.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old right handed woman with epilepsy following stroke in 2004, last seizure 1 week ago with left arm jerking followed by confusion.

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  A EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow-up study may be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old right handed woman with juvenile myoclonic epilepsy, seizure free for many years.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Both drowsiness and hyperventilation are characterized by an increase in theta with some paroxysmal bursts of theta.  There is also some left temporal 5 Hz activity picked up in hyperventilation with a characteristic morphology of rhythmic midtemporal theta of drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.

IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No generalized spike and wave activity was noted.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  In this particular epilepsy
syndrome, this normal EEG pattern, with absence of epileptiform activity in an adult is quite common.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female with seizures since age 14, presents with refractory episodes, here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta activity seen diffusely throughout the EEG.  During the recording, the patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  The only activating procedure that is performed is hyperventilation, during which she has an episode which I will describe below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Events:  During this recording, while the patient was doing hyperventilation she suddenly stopped responding, started moving her throat and jerking her back and forth repeatedly.  At times she would move to the left and then to the right.  During this episode, the tech stimulated her feet and she would respond and at times appeared to follow commands, but would not verbalize.  The whole episode of unresponsiveness lasted some minutes, but with the clinical presentation lasted about 12 minutes.  During this recording, the EEG revealed prominent muscle artifact but a nice posterior dominant rhythm could be seen at times and normal EEG could be seen at times throughout the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG with an episode of unresponsiveness as described above with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a nonepileptic event, likely psychogenic in nature.  Otherwise this is a normal awake EEG and no seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 70-80 microvolt alpha rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth are noted.  The alpha rhythm is a little higher amplitude on the left than the right.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, increasing the amplitude of the background as well as increasing beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include rhythmic central theta and frontocentral beta as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG is wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted, although there were many normal, youthful waveforms such as posterior slow waves of youth. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing stage 2 sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old left handed woman with lupus, endometriosis, cerebral palsy, chest pain, and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, Zoloft, Oxycontin, Morphine, Klonopin, Prednisone, Singulair.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation is completed.  The patient experiences two of her typical seizures during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient's seizure is identified and is characterized in the EEG at 11:26.  The patient has eye flutter and trembling of the left hand.  She is somewhat interactive with the tech but does not answer questions until the event is over.  The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout the event.  When the event ends, the patient becomes a little bit drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.
During photic stimulation, the patient starts shaking her head.  There are no epileptiform features, just a normal driving response.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The behaviors described above did not have an EEG signature.  They are relatively characteristic of nonepileptic seizures.  If additional information is needed, EEG monitoring may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  19 year old left handed male admitted on April 22, 2012 with new onset seizure characterized by loss of consciousness, face falling forward from a standing position, with 2 minute tonic clonic seizure, followed by 5-10 minutes of confusion.  Past history of seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Percocet,
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm of 40 mV.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in theta, following this the patient becomes drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in both beta and theta.  Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep.  Vertex waves are slightly asymmetric.
In stage I and stage II sleep frontal beta is quite prominent. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.  The patient is drifting into and out of stage II sleep during photic stimulation, which does not otherwise activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Asymmetry in the vertex waves could be related to a head measuring error, therefore, this should not be considered pathological.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed female with episode of shaking, increased heart rate, rapid breathing followed by left arm shaking which progressed to the whole body.  The patient awake and aware of the episode.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal single lead EEG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTY:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation produced no abnormal discharges, however, see below for photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  During photic stimulation, the patient started having slow movements of her head side to side then started twitching her upper extremities and moving her body towards the right side and appeared to be unresponsive to commands.  This episode lasted for a period of about 40 seconds and then she remained with her eyes closed and appeared to be slightly more responsive.  Minutes later, photic stimulation was performed again after she had opened her eyes and appeared to have followed commands.  At that point she started jerking her left shoulder slowly, then trembling her upper extremities and again falling towards the right side of the seat.  This second episode lasted for about approximately a minute and 20 seconds.  During both episodes, the EEG revealed a normal awake background with no epileptiform abnormalities and no EEG correlate to this behavior described above.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with two episodes of shaking during photic stimulation with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG with no seizures or epileptiform discharges.  The episodes captured above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with nonepileptic events.  No seizure.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient's EEG was reviewed using continuous spike and seizure detection software, in addition to the patient's learned event as well as nurses' notes.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a mild excessive amount of beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and stage III sleep, as well as stage IV.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   None
SEIZURE/EVENT:  During the recording, the patient presses the alarm around 7:39 p.m. and describes that she feels like she is going to have an event.  There are no EEG changes at that time.  At 09:24:51, the patient presses the alarm and starts shaking her body, arching her back, and stretching her legs.  She lifts up the sheets at times and cannot be seen in the video.  She continues to do this for about 7 to 8 minutes until nurses come in and she is unresponsive to questions.  She remains having irregular jerking movements.  During this entire time, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The episode captured during this EEG had no EEG correlate, which is consistent with a nonepileptic psychogenic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed man, with a history of seizures with Xanax withdrawal, anxiety, and hypertension, presents for episodes of strange things in mouth with quick recall of events.  He is here for classification of epileptic versus non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.  Continues spike wave detection and seizure detection software was used to review the event, along with the patient's alarms, nurses notes, and clinical notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1, stage 2, and deep stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENT:  During the recording the patient had 5 events where he would suddenly start shaking his head from side to side.  Sometimes towards the left and sometimes toward the right irregularly while becoming unresponsive and remaining so for minutes at time, sometimes for more than 5-10 minutes, and intermittently starting and stopping the behavior.  These  episodes, the first one which occurred at 3:28 p.m., the second one occurred at 9:23 p.m., the third one occurred around 2:40 a.m., and another one at 7:51 a.m., and the last one at 8:48 am had no EEG correlate other than a muscle artifact and afterwards there was normal posterior dominant rhythm seen, all consistent with nonepileptic events.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episodes captured above with head shaking had no EEG correlate.  As such, they are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic events. Please note that this patient had previous records which showed left temporal sharp waves.  This was not seen during this admission.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed female syncopal spell lasting 25 seconds.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and a sleep record in very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, exceeding 70 mV with posterior slow waves of youth.  In drowsiness there is hypersynchronous rhythmic higher amplitude theta frequency activity “hypnogogic”, “hypersynchrony”.  There were 1 or 2 points of head rocking artifact and there were 1-2 bursts which are slightly asynchronous. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude, somewhat sharply contoured theta frequency activity, but no definitive spike and wave activity. The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Other features of drowsiness include the hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG demonstrates multiple normal variants for a young adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There was no definitive spike and wave activity, although hyperventilation did produce some rhythmic high amplitude theta.  There were a handful of slightly asynchronous bursts as the patient transitions to drowsiness.  If absence seizures are an important consideration, a repeat fasting EEG, perhaps with a second hyperventilation session maybe helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old man with a history of TBI in 1998, admitted after having an episode of tonic-clonic seizure, brought to the emergency department where he had another seizure and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Pantoprazole, Depakote
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 2 events in this recording similar to the ones in the previous day.  The first one occurred at 8:10:43 p.m. and the second one occurred at 11:47 p.m.  Both of them, the body had irregular shaking for minutes with no response to verbal or motor commands.  The patient had no EEG correlate during this time despite being unconscious.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes described above had no EEG correlate, as such it is consistent with nonepileptic seizures.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG during wakefulness.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.

MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab  using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9 to 10 Hz in frequency, 30 to 40 microvolt in amplitude seen the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple/frequencies and resulted in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 to 70 beats per minute and regular.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  A 10:00:43 the patient reported that she has an attack described as her stomach is jumping with her arm on top of it.  She added that this is part of her attack.  At 10:06:01 she reported that she is feeling hot.  At 10:11:54 she stated that she is seeing blinking red stuff that hurts.  EEG showed a normal awake pattern with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz.  Eye blink artifact, lateral eye movement artifacts and muscle artifact with no epileptiform activity during this event.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.  The episodes were characterized by clinical events of jumping stomach, feeling hot, and seeing blinking red stuff without any significant EEG correlation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This study does not support the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The episodes are diagnostic for psychogenic nonepileptiform events.  Although this study does not exclude the possibility of epilepsy and intermittent seizures, if seizures are a clinical concern a prolonged ambulatory EEG may be helpful to capture other types of events.

INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.    Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with epilepsy since age 12.  Subsequent cocaine dependence.  After a seizure, patient became violent.  Seizures characterized by an aura of strange feeling followed by postictal confusion.  Last seizure 1 day ago. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures.  The technologist told him that, that was a possibility.  The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the EEG and produces and increase an amplitude of the background.  Vertex waves and POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep with brief stage 2 sleep.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
The patient had an event during photic stimulation.  The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep.
The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly.  His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM.
Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event.
There were no epileptiform features noted during the event.  No postictal features were identified.
Heart rate 78-150 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  The EEG is normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient had an unusual behavior.  The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep.  The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this individual.  The first EEG immediately after his symptoms was associated with left temporal focal slowing, but this EEG is normal.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old right-handed man with a history of head trauma from car accident.  The patient stated that he started having seizure-like activity after car accident.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II of sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 12 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through a stage 2 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy, if seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 36-year-old woman with a history of complex partial seizures with last seizure reported in 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 10-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Excessive diffuse beta is observed.
During sleep symmetrical vertex waves are captured.
Hyperventilation produces a mild diffuse background slowing.
Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 22 minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, the patient's sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with the patient asleep may be of benefit.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication effects, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with a past medical history of adult onset seizures who presented with 2 episodes of generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  The patient remained lethargic.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Records were daily reviewed for EEG abnormalities and clinical events, wakefulness, stage 2 sleep, and a slow wave sleep were captured.  There was an automated spike and seizure detection system in place as well as the patient activated alarm system.  The patient was drowsy with short periods of wakefulness during this recording.
Interictal EEG:  In the most alert state, there was a posterior dominant rhythm with a frequency of 9-9.5 Hz and 25-40 microvolts seen in the occipital region, which attenuated with eye opening.  There was presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta frequency, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness, stage 1 and a stage 2 sleep were seen during the most part of this recording.  Stage 1 sleep was characterized by the disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, vertex sharp waves, and POSTS.  Stage 2 sleep was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles, and POSTS.  The deeper stages of sleep have characterized by increasing amounts of delta frequency activity.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures were captured during this recording.  Heart rate was 90 to 110 beats per minute.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  No clinical events were captured during this recording.  The patient was drowsy, but arousable by calling the patient.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG monitoring study capturing short periods of wakefulness and for the most part of the recording drowsiness stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  This EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are of a clinical concern, a repeat prolonged video EEG monitoring may be helpful.  Please note that the patient was tachycardiac.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted with an episode of transient dizziness.  Past history of hypertension, asthma and a psychiatric illness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, lisinopril, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was attempted in the laboratory using standard a 10-20 System of electrode placement, with 1 channel of EKG.  Significant technical difficulties included the hair weaves that the patient has.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems with electrode placement and impedance, the background EEG is appropriately organized, with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  The referential montage was not particularly successful.  Features of drowsiness included an increase in background slowing.  In addition, very brief stage I sleep was seen, with vertex waves and then a transition in and out of stage I sleep.  At the very close of the record, the patient was transitioning in and out of stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 84 bpm, occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The transitions in and out of stage II sleep may reflect sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance, which could be correlated with this patient's clinical picture.  To obtain a better quality EEG, a repeat study, when the patient has had her hair weaves removed, is suggested.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of beta throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
The heart rate is 54.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EPISODES:
During the recording as photic stimulation was being performed the patient started stuttering and her right arm started shaking and trembling for a period of 11 minutes.  The patient is responsive throughout the whole period; however, the code word which she was asked to memorize and later asked to repeat was repeated incorrectly at the end of the event.  During this event the EEG appeared to be normal with no epileptiform activity seen or EEG correlate seen.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episode described above, which started on with the right arm shaking did not reveal any EEG correlate, as such it may represent a nonepileptic event or alternatively it may be a simple partial seizure, which in up to 75% of the cases do not have any EEG correlate.  Lastly, please note that the excessive beta noted on the EEG may be due to a medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013.  Apparently she fainted and was on the floor for 15 seconds and then was observed to shake.  Of note, during the recording here in the laboratory, there was a brief episode of right hemibody tingling.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The recording start time was 11:29 a.m.  The recording end time was 12 noon.  The recording length was 25 minutes.
As the record opens there is a well formed and symmetric 9-10 Hz  posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness.  She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela.  During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges. CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman, seizure free for 1-2 years.  Characteristics of seizures included oral automatisms and tongue biting, positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, multivitamins, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a routine outpatient EEG with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1 and T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, rhythmic midtemporal theta activity was noted with 5 Hz activity seen infrequently, left more so than the right.  Stage 2 sleep was captured at the close of the recording with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  No temporal theta was noted at that time.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but produced vigorous bilateral driving response with supraharmonic driving.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this subject which did not identify epileptiform activity.  The rhythmic midtemporal theta noted in drowsiness is a normal variant.
